\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 It's often like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes. Yes. Mm. Yes, quite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 If you had any problems would you go to your father with them as you grew older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Always your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How did they expect you to behave towards them, your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well to use civility.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you think on the whole you and your brothers and sisters would be well behaved towards your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes. Yes, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you say that they were quite strict in their upbringing of their children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did they bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh we got - we all got on - very well together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 If somebody hit you, another child outside your family, did they say you should hit the child back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh my father said, be as - that is what my father said, he says, always fight 'em back. He says, learn to take your own part.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well that I would - that I wouldn't know. I mean I would - I don't know what was in their mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did they bring you up to consider certain things important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well I don't know. Although - some time ago I - you see, even when I was a youngster I was also had - a business mind. I used
 to supply - small things to various people. I went to a shop in Canning Town - I was recommended to go there by my barber, his son-in-law had opened a shop, a barber's shop and - and fancy good. I took a small attached case of a few samples and I showed 
i
t to this man. The profit that I would have earnt - that would have been the fare money to go there and back, was about - well the order come to five shillings, and I - I think I'd earnt about - perhaps a shilling, and that would have just paid the fare m
o
ney. Well I was in two minds whether to take him this order. Then my father - I told my father about it and he says to me, your word should be your bond. He says, you deliver the order. I delivered the order - from five shillings it become ten shillings, 
from ten shillings it become a pound. And at the finish it become up to five pound orders. And that is a fact.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I must have been about - seventeen. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Is that in your spare time you were doing that or was that regular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, that was in my spare time. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Where would you go and get the things from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well I would - I - I would go to wholesalers. See they used to be one street in Houndsditch that was all wholesale warehouses. Actually I - I really 
started when I come out of the army. And then I started - dabbling, you understand. 'Course I mean money - money - money was small, you couldn't buy a lot for your money, well you could buy a lot for money, if you had the money, you understand. But of cou
rse - when you persevere it gets bigger.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What sort of things would one buy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well - I'm working with a cousin of mine, and we both had sixpence each. That was pocket money. Spent our - that was my pocket money from my job. We walked through - Mid
dlesex Street, and - there was a street there called Stoney Lane, and we looked - there was - there was a shop there, a bar - a barber's shop and he had a few - lines on - in his window. And the person who the shop belonged to says, come in the shop boys.
 
He said, have you got any money? I said, I've got sixpence and my cousin said he's got sixpence, he says, well - I'll sell you a half a dozen, six treasure note cases. They were the flap type, that - that fold over. Wonder if you know the sort I mean? One
 
was like a cross - a cross inside, a piece of ribbon, and the other one was like two strips, you put in the ten shilling note, you turned it over and it - it holds it. So we bought six of them for the shilling. He says, go in the Lane and sell 'em at sixp
e
nce each. He says, what you don't sell bring back and you'll get your money back at what you paid for 'em. We went there and we sold the six. Come to three shillings. We kept - we kept working these - treasure note cases for some weeks. Then they ran out.
 Then we started buying some matchbox cases. And matchbox \endash 
 enameled matchbox case with a badge of - of reg - regiments, you see, because the war had started, 1914. And - we're paying, I think it was - four shillings a dozen. And selling 'em for sixpence. W
ell by that time we - we'd had a few shillings you see, we've - we've saved. And - we start selling them. Later, my cousin, he says he doesn't want to sell these things any more, so we - dissolve partnership. Well I carried on. Now - the next thing I sold
 
was Wrigley's spearmint chewing gum, at a penny a bar. I don't know what it is today. The price of it today. I mean old penny. And I used to have a tray round my - well on two straps and scream out, penny a bar Wrigleys, and the coppers - the coppers - I 
u
sed to finish up, I used to have about - four or five hundred, you know, pennies on the tray you know, sell 'em all out. Well from that another time - another time - I see a crowd, there used to be a station called Aldgate East station, it's not there tod
a
y, but - there is a New Aldgate station further up. I see a crowd there and being a - youngster I went to see what the crowd was, what - what it was all about. They were distribut - distributing newspapers, so I think I bought two quire of papers, newspap
e
rs, 'cos they were sold them days at a penny - a penny. And - I finished up half way round London, selling these papers, selling - buying 'em off of other people and selling 'em again. I finished up - I made a profit. But I think I may have had about twel
v
e news - papers left, 'course I had to throw 'em away. But - it carried on you know what I mean and - that's what - that's what made me start market life. 'Cos - years ago - regarding - fuel - besides - gas lamps in the streets - for markets and - and the
 
fair - the fair - the fairgrounds, see, used to use the - paraffin-flare - flare lamps. The flare-lamp. You know what a flare lamp is? Well switch off and I'll tell you. Well, I mean I've got to describe it. It's more like a triangle - with a tube at the 
b
ottom, in other words it looks like a kite in metal, paraffin is poured inside it, as - there's a tube at the bottom with some holes on and a burner, you see. Well that is put on the ground - and you'd light some paper, and - after about - a couple of min
utes, you turn on the tap and it - and it's - it flares out, and it gives a lovely warmth and gives a lovely light, they used to hang these up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 They'd be hanging would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would each stall have one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That's right. And also the fairgrounds used to have them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were they ever dangerous?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no. No, no, no, they wasn't dangerous at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you work in markets round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I've worked - there used to be a market in Aldgate. In Aldgate itself. Used 
to start from Leman Street up to the Min - what they call the Minories. That was a very nice market. That's when they had the trams. Now years ago - between the 1900's they used to have trams with horses. Fire engines with horses. And the horses used to h
a
ve bells. Instead of the - what they've got today, like there used to be bells round the horses - neck and on it's body and as - as they used to rush round the turnings, going about - perhaps about twenty miles an hour, it was marvellous to see 'em go rou
n
d these corners without - going over. It was a sight to be seen. And we also used to go for rides, we used to go up the West End, we used to come back in a hansom carriage, about four chaps, all pay so much each you know. It was very interesting you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 When you were a boy selling all these things would you go out of this area at all or did you always stick near home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh I didn't care where I went as long as I - made a profit. I was once - bought some - the Jewish new year card. Now in Commerci
al Road there's - it's still a market but it's called Morgan Street, well about that time - there used to be - a big - crowd of people come from - from - Poland - and they used to congregate in the East End of London. The market there was called the Jewis
h
 market, Morgan Street. And on the corner of that street was a printers. I - got a barrow and board for sixpence, I stood outside that shop, I went inside the shop and I bought some - some of these Jewish New Year cards. And I - was selling 'em outside th
e printers shop although it was - I sold 'em out, I went in the shop and I bought some more. He saw me doing it, he didn't say nothing. Didn't worry him. Only done that once. Same as the newspapers, I only did it once. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 And then you'd go on to another line of some sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you invest the money you made in something else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh definitely, oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Or did you spend it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no, I - I invested in something else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You didn't give any of it to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no. No. I mean - when I - when I start working I was giving her - what I - what I - all the wages all but sixpence you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 But not when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no, no. Yes, yes. There was a chap - who used to live in our 
- he used to live in our house, see, because they divided up into flats you see these houses, and - he used to sell - he used to sell - he used to go to Billingsgate market, used to sell fish in the morning, sell his fish out by ten o'clock in the morning
.
 Then he'd - have fruit. Sell the fruit out. Now that man - he went to - used to go to these hol - holiday places you know like Blackheath - Hampstead Heath, he went to Blackheath, he took the barrow all the way. When you get to Black - Blackheath you hav
e
 to go up a hill. He goes up the hill with his - he was selling, I think it was pineapple. He goes up on the heath - heath he has a good day. He's coming down the hill, he slips, bar - barrow goes on on top of him. He's laid up for six months in the hospi
t
al, this man. When the war breaks out, he says to me, go down the Lane and see if you can find me some cardboard. He says, I'll take all the thick cardboard you can get. He's taken on an order with the - Government for repairing - Army shoes. Army boots. 
S
o what did he want the paper - the cardboard for? So I go there, I take a barrow, and I take two or three sacks, the market's over, there's plenty of cardboard there, I pick up all the thick pieces I can find and I take it to him. He used to give me ten s
h
illings. You know what he used to do? He'd rip off - rip off the sole, the first sole you understand, the thin sole, put on a sheet of cardboard, you know, measured the size, and then put a thin sole of leather. Oh yes, that's a fact. He finished up he op
ened a - a boot shop - two big boot shops in Kensington Road. I also met him in the country, selling shoes. Of course - he's died now but his sons are - quite well off.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 The ten shillings which you got though must have been quite a lot in those days wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, yes. I'll tell you something else. A brother of mine - he says to me, his - a friend so his has got - some \endash 
 second hand \endash  second hand stalls where they sell second hand clothes but done up. Gents suits, understand, they clean '
em and press 'em. In fact the place is still there, it's - called a clothe - a clothiers market, in Cutler Street. Cutler Street is just near Houndsditch. And it's been there, well as long as I can remember. He says, you go there, he says, he wants you to
 
- take a stall there, like he's got. And he had - shirts - vest - vests and shirts. And years ago the best used to be all fashionable, in fact it's coming back now. He says to me, I should sell the shirts at a shilling each - and the vest at two shillings
. Now I had the - you know what the - Alaska is? Alaska? They come from abroad, that's right, yes, yes, yes. Well they used to wear these \{BLANK\}
 you know what I mean. And - I must have had about twenty come round asking the prices. They've offered me - I t
old them a shilling the shirts, two shillings the vests. They've offered me I think sixpence for the shirts, and about a shilling for the vests. So of course I told them to go away. Well they come up the following week another crowd come up the following 
week, and I says, the vests are ten shillings each, and the shirts are five shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 The same ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
No, I'd put the - no, I don't know if - they were the same or - but - quite a lot of that type of - that type of people came up. So I think they
 offered me - half a crown for the - no, about three shillings for the - for the vests, and about - I know I made - I made a - a very big profit. Well - I had such a crowd and they were so many of them spending that the governor left his stall and came ov
e
r and helped to serve. He used to give me a shilling and my breakfast you see. Well for the - what I used to do. This time he gave me ten shillings, and my breakfast. But only once, it was only the first time, you understand. But ten bob - that ten bob wa
s a fortune. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were you quite good at selling though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well - everything's experience. I can demonstrate, I can - see a line I've never seen in my life, and - with a little - finding out one or two things I can give a demonstration, you unde
rstand? There was a line - there was a line I bought, it was called - it was called a footpad, the footpad, it was like - about inch and a half - long, inch and a half long, by - by three quarters of a inch in width. It looked like a piece of salt. Now th
a
t was one of the finest lines I've ever seen. They were liquidation of stock, how a firm can go into liquidation I don't know. It was for removing corns and the hard skin. Now I myself have had - corns - not corns but hard skin - under my feet for years a
n
d years, and whatever I used to try, I'd take 'em - I'd cut - take some away but they always come back. I used this, just - all you had to do was just dip it in the water, and rub it on. And the first time I used it I thought to myself, I'm going to have 
p
ain. I rubbed it, I just couldn't feel anything. No pain whatsoever, and - it took 'em right off. Well I tried it two or three times and since then I've never - I've never had any hard skin. Now the people I've only sold - who I - who only bought it, hund
r
eds of people bought it. In fact, for - about four years I had people asking me if I had anymore, it was such a wonderful line. Another line I also sold was - there was a cloth, it must have been about two foot long by eighteen inches in width, actually t
h
ere was two cloths, one was - one was for - polishing, the other was for rubbing it over afterwards again. I bought that also as a clearing line but - they - it was marked in German, was - it must have - it was made in Germany you see but there was German
 
instructions on the - in the cellophane packet. And I just bought a dozen to try and see - see if the line was any good. I mean the lines weren't any good you were competent you know to sell it. We got it home, we - we had for a present when we got marrie
d
 a pair of silver candlesticks. Now as a rule whatever polish you use it generally takes a time and you make your hands all dirty as well. Well I got one of these rags and I just went - switched it round, in two seconds - in two seconds it cleaned the thi
n
g up. What I did, I cleaned up a penny. I cleaned up a penny with some - at the same time with - metal polish you understand, only done one side. Then I took this rag and rubbed her over and you should have seen this penny. Used to go out - I used to go -
 
out to the market, I used to take the cloth, and I'd take this penny, didn't let people see the side that I'd cleaned but I'd say, now you see this penny? I've just gone like that and like that and turned her over, you know what I mean, and - you know, it
'
s a brand new penny. In other words I'm - I'm - I'm cheating them. Know what I'm talking about. And the amount that I only sold, I must have had two taxi loads full of 'em. A clearing line but I sold a lot. That's - that's now and again that you can pick 
up a winner, you understand what I mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you quite enjoy doing that when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
No, no, I won't say - I won't say as a boy. It wasn't as a boy. No, no, no, I was grown up at the time. But when I - when I - when I was a boy I didn't h
ave that money to spend. I mean - I - I could spend - a thousand pound - if - if I had a line that I knew was going to earn me three thousand pound, you understand But when I was a boy, if I had thirty shillings it was a lot of money. You understand.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you quite enjoy doing it though, did you enjoy selling and getting around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh of course you did, sure, that was my life. Of course I enjoyed it. Same as I - I enjoyed going to conferences and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were you allowed to swear in your house, would your father let you swear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, no, no. In fact - I'm sending this off today. That is the - what I - that is what I belong to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 National Market Traders Federation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 And that's what you did a lot of work with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I got - I got - I've got some more members you see, so I'm sending off - sending off some cheques you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 When you were a boy, if grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes. Oh yes, oh yes, sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Your parents wouldn't mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 If you did something your parents didn't approve of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well - over a stool. Over a stool. You know, a - a - or a form - and father would take off his strap - have one or two on - on your backside. And - we wouldn't do them things again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 This was only your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes. No, mother wouldn't interfere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would this have to be something quite serious before your father would hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh definitely. Oh yes, yes, sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you remember any particular occasion when you were punished for anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No. Well I was - I was but I can't remember the occasion.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How did you feel about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I was wrong. I just felt I was wrong, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you think you got your ideas about how to behave from both of your parents, or did one of them play a particular part?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 My father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You think your father influenced you more than your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no. What do you mean by influenced?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you think your ideas on how you should behave, do you think your father played more of a part in that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, my mother. My - my mother. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What about when you had a birthday, would this be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I don't think so, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Party or cards or presents or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
No, no. Oh I know my - my - wife - always sends my - my son - he's twenty-nine now - from his first year she's - been sending cards every year, and she always buys a cake and one or two presents, but my parents - I don't th
ink they thought about them things them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 So you didn't have a cake or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, I don't - I don't think so, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You wouldn't have celebrated Christmas, what would you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, we cele - yes, we - yes - oh yes, we
 had Christmas. Oh yes, definitely. I mean that we'd look forward the same as - other - anybody else would look forward too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were there any other religious holidays you'd actually celebrate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well - all the Jewish - festivals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you celebrate all those, were you an orthodox family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well - I am - I - at the time they were orthodox, you see. Very orthodox. In fact - they wouldn't - light a fire a Saturday, they would get someone come in. And give 'em a couple of coppers, to light a f
ire, that was a regular occurrence. Any - any bread - Passover - would be - put - in a bin and set light to, old bread. Old bread. Or given away to somebody. Also - at that time they would keep all crockery, this is Passover crockery, that is kept separat
e
. It was only taken out Passover. Whether it was - cups and saucers, plates - cooking utensils, that was all separate. But - I'm not orthodox and my wife is not orthodox now, although - her father was very religious. He was the type of man, he'd sooner st
arve himself and give away to somebody else. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 People would all have the day off work for the Jewish holidays would they? How would you celebrate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well - if it's - it it's a feast day they would feast, if it's a fast they would fast, you under
stand. See, the - there's one - holiday, the New Year, it's called Yon Kippur. Even very very - terrific firms - even a firm like C }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
 A's, now C. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760  A's are - Cohen and Abraham, now a lot of people don't know that. In fact, I may get into trouble. Also Rons
on - it's A. Ronson isn't it? Aronson, is Ronson, and there's many many big firms - Walson, Jewish. Now quite a lot of these big stores, Marks and Spencer\rquote 
s, do you know they started in the markets? They started in Leeds a penny - a penny bazaar. Nothing over a penny. That's how they started.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Even these big firms would give their workers the day off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh definitely. Oh yes, yes, yes. Yes, sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Is Yon Kippur a feasting holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, no, no, that's a fasting holiday. You only fea - you on
ly feast when the holiday's over, but then after - if you've starved all day long, you don't feel much like eating, and if you do eat you- you're going to have a stomach ache the next day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you remember your mother making great preparations for the eating, for meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, oh yes, oh yes, definitely. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you have anything special on these holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Passover, yes. Passover, there's the unleavened bread, motzas. All the - various things like according to the - what's in the - 
Jewish books - and the reason - the reason - why they hold the Passover - there's a bone and there's something else, they put a radish or something else, you know what I mean, all them things on a plate, a bottle of wine - in case - in case the - Lord com
es down, they'd leave a bottle of wine on - in the evening, on the first night, what they call the first cider. That was all them things you know. 'Course when it's fa - when it's fasting they fast and when it's feast they feast.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 In your family you'd observe Christmas though would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh - oh yes, but - it - if - if a - if a - any purpose we ever spoke about Christ my father would go mad. You understand? But - I think myself it's a good thing - thing that Christ - came to this earth because the 
amount of people that made a business over Christmas - the amount of spending, you understand? Oh it is true. That's one thing I used to look forward to Christmas, you see, if it wasn't for Christmas we'd starve - after Christmas because January, February
, March there's nothing doing at all. In fact - years ago, if you remember there used to be plenty of pawn shops about. Today they are jewellers shops. Years ago after Christmas all the poor people would take all their - what belongings they had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You were saying about when your father used to make out bills?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Use. When my father used to make out bills - he'd put down an estimated price - you know, what he should be paid for the job, but he never got so much, they always gave him less. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 There was no way of collecting it from people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You just had to accept this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
That's right, that's right. And sometimes he had to borrow money - for the materials - for doing the particular job you see, so he used to borrow or a
sk for a sub, you see, to buy the tools - or to buy the material rather, to do the particular job. See, because - he may be owed money from say two or three places, so he's rather short, so he's got to do another job you see, so while he's waiting for the
 money he's got to - get a sub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Presumably you're always waiting for people to pay bills?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
That's right, that's right. That's right. Mm. Even today with cheques. That's the worst of - some of these places, you have to wait months and months for cheques. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were there any really poor people living anywhere near you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You mentioned pawn shops, were there quite a lot of pawnshops in this part of London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes, there - there was quite a lot, and - during the - strike, I can't remember w
hat year it was, when there were thousands of people out of work - they used to pawn their medals. Now they got so many medals that they just didn't know what to do with 'em. So later on they asked all these people who - who give their medals, have to inc
l
ude a west-gate, a waistcoat with these medals, and they had windows full of them. I think about - that's all I can say about pawnshops, but - I think I told you before that - Christmastime, after people had a Christmas, the poor people had to - pawn what
ever they could so as to have some money to spend, because they spent it all Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 People weren't pawning things like jewellery, they were pawning things like household effects?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Pardon? Say - say new suits of clothes if they had any, wedding
 rings. Anything they could find like that was a little value, then on a later date they could take - take - take - take 'em out you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How much would you get would you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well they would give perhaps a sixth of the value. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 And they were always quite honest, pawnbrokers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh definitely. 'Course you had to pay them back a bit - a percentage you see. But of course the pawn - pawnshops - the pawnbrokers, they had - they have to keep these articles for six months you see, 
then - they're sold by a public auction, you see, so the au - so the - pawn - pawnbrokers - have to try and realize back their money, which they do, and then if they wish they can buy some of these goods back themselves, see, for a little extra, because I
 mean they - more or less they know the value of these articles and they know what to - bid for 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 There were a lot of public houses were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes. Oh yes, there were - quite a - well there still are plenty of public houses, but of course 
me as a beer drinker, I don't go much to the pubs. The only time I do have a drink - is when I - when I used to go to meetings. Meeting I regard public houses - public houses in the old days, there was always sawdust on the floor, and there were spittoons
 
- now - beer - was three ha'pence a pint - and - a half a pint was a penny. Whisky was ten shillings a bottle. Cigarettes were five for a penny, and the better class cigarette was ten for tuppence ha'penny, including a box of matches. You could buy - twel
v
e boxes of matches for one farthing. Now - that's - that's a fact, yes. You could buy a large packet of tea for a penny. A jug of milk for a penny. Small cakes - they were a farthing and a ha'penny each. Bread rolls were three a penny. And sweets - six ou
n
ces to eight ounces for one penny. Our fares, what we pay now three new pennies was a ha'penny and a penny. News papers were a penny, and the Sunday newspaper, a much bigger paper, was tuppence. A familiar sight that we don't see today, was the - what's h
e
 called now, the muffin man. He'd carry a big tray balanced on his head and he - and he'd ring a hand bell, and scream out, muffins. And 'course he'd sell quite a lot. There was also the bootblack, they used to stand on the kerbs and they used to charge -
 I'm not sure if it was a ha'penny or a penny to clean the shoes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 A lot of men actually would never clean their shoes at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no. Yes, yes, yes, quite. They'd have their shoes cleaned. And there was also - just like you see - baked c
hestnuts, they used to sell hot potatoes, with a little salt and a little butter, like a baked potato. Also, there's one thing we do not see today and that is the - 'course there - there are one or two about because - they're not used, in fact they used t
h
em as - for - for - more like a garden, but there's the old horse water trough where the horses used to stop to have a drink. Also - another thing that we don't see today was a Salvation Army band. Where the lassies used to play their tambourines, the men
 
played their trumpets and they would sing. And - actually - where it first started, it started on a corner - of Cambridge Heath Road and Whitechapel - General Booth, he used to - he first started, when he used to try and go in the pubs and tell the people
 
about - religion, they used to mock and jeer him, and that is the reason why they've got his statue there today. Have you ever seen it? Just by - just by - what they call Mile End Waste. That's where Cambridge Heath Road is and the beginning of Mile End R
oad, there is like a little green there and his statue is there. And ever now and again I believe it's once a year, the Salvation Army come down and make a big fuss.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you think they achieved anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Pardon? Oh definite - that's me - that's me
, yes. Because once upon a time they were jeered and they wouldn't take no notice and - now if you ever see 'em there was - there was always crowds of people round, because they had a very good band, and - they could sing and got people interested. Oh the
r
e's another thing I'd like to mention - about houses. A house - that today they are asking about - I'd say from twelve thousand to - to fifteen thousand pound could be bought in 1930 and to include a garage, six hundred pound. Now that - you reckon the pe
rcentage of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What would a house cost earlier than that? What would a house cost round about 1910?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well that - that I wouldn't know. I - because - regarding the one at six hundred pound and that's my sister bought one at Hendon - that was ab
out 1930, and you see the houses today, well they're only asking - and I'm - I really can't understand why the Government allow it. Yes, yes, yes, yes. Sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 It's a criminal thing really isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Of course it is. Sure. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How did you spend Saturday in those days when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well - I don't think I spent it any other was - than - than - than playing with the children in the street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What about Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well Sunday more or less the same thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you go to a synagogue?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh yes, yes, yes, yes. That was called a Talmatora, Talmatora, that's like a house of learning. Oh - I believe it was every day. Every day - except Saturday. The Saturday was the seventh, 'cos my people were orthodox you understand, and we h
ad to do as we were told.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 So would you do anything special on a Saturday, any religious observance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no. Oh no. No. No, nol No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That was a free day was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes. Saturdays was the seventh - day of rest you see. Of course, we 
- I - as children we would play in the street, you know what I mean as usual, in the Square rather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What were these Talmatora like, what did you do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well we used to learn - learn the - the prayers - the blessing - the grace - grace, you kn
ow, make grace before meals and all that. And - we learnt - the alphabet, and also the - the writing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Could you speak Hebrew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I can't speak Hebrew, no. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You could read it could you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I could - understand - oh yes, I could understand quite a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you wear different clothes on the seventh day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, yes. Always had on new suits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were you allowed to play any games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Not on the Saturday, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What would you have to do? Stay inside or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no, we were allowed to go out. We're allowed to go out and - play, there's - nothing about that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would your parents go to any synagogue or anywhere like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh definitely, definitely. My father used to go ev
ery morning, every morning - he used to get up about - six o'clock, go seven o'clock to the synagogue, every morning regular. Oh yes, yes. And he'd still carry on today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would your mother go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I don't think so, no, she stopped at home. Of course 
holiday times - the - the - well we all went to synagogue you understand, synagogue when they used to hold the like - various festivals you know. And it's a very sad thing if a boy - a young boy gets - what they call \{ILLEGIBLE\}
, he's thirteen from birth s
o he becomes a man. He has to say - learn a prayer to say it in Hebrew. Well I was at one about - four weeks ago, and the service took from nine o'clock 'til twelve. Well I honestly thought there was about - they were doing it for about a half a dozen boy
s
, there was just my nephew. There was just my nephew - and the rabbis, I mean they were saying their prayers, the boy had to say his part, they opened the canopy and they took out the - the holy of holies, you understand, and - they took - they took it al
l
 round the synagogue, it was a very large synagogue, and later on they took it back and they blessed it and all that you know. And then later - later on they held a - there was a celebration at the - Strand - Strand Pal - the Regent - Regent Palace Hotel,
 from eight o'clock 'til about - I think it was eleven or twelve o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Had there always been this ceremony?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, definitely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you have some sort of ceremony when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I didn't, but my - my son did. I made for my son.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 It was only for boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 'cos I had to learn it - I had to learn it at the time, but we didn't have no - special occasion like they make today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 This is a more recent thing is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes, that's right, that's right, yes, yes, yes. Se
e people of today are earning bigger money, you understand, they can afford the - have bigger things you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Would you go there, you said you went there every day, would you go there before you went to ordinary school? Or would you go in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh we used to go in the evenings, to the Talmatora, yes, in - like - not in the evenings, after school - after school say - about - five or six o'clock. Yes, in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you mind doing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, I used to - I - I didn't mind - wouldn't mind. I mean it was a matter of must.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 It's what your family obviously expected from you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
That's right, that's right, yes, yes, sure. It's the same as - same as - people go to - like a - the younger church, Sunday school and all that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you have any youth activities apart from going to the actual lessons and learning things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, no, no, no, there was one - it was called the - oh I can't remember now - Oxford - Oxford and St George's club, that was at - right opp
osite where I went to school, Bett Street, where I didn't have the sense at the time, you understand - to - try and join a club like that. See. I mean if the masters would have informed us, you see, - we would have done, but they - just didn't. I did go -
 I did go to some - evening classes, you know for a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you belong to a choir at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 In the school, only in the school. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would they run any outings from your Talmatora?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No. No. No. No. No. Only - only in the school we used 
to when - when I was a child, they used to have what they call play centres. Yes. Like a play centre so - it was in the same school, just going into a different room - and - there was like various things to - to make - make and play with, you know what I 
mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 When would that be held?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
I think it was about once a - once a week. Then you went to - then - then you had to be a good boy, you see, there was no - there was no mixed classes. There was boys in the boys school, in the same school there was
 girls in the girls side you see. You had to be a good boy, you had to be - pun - punctual going to - school - not make a noise in the class and you have a - they used to give you like a blue ticket. If you had a blue ticket you could go that - that week 
to - to a play centre. Only of course I was quite young at the time then you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 If you weren't you weren't allowed to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no. No. No. Oh - that's right, a kind of reward yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you say any sort of grace at meals, did you bless food in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes. Mm. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you say prayers, would your family have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Who would lead them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh, father, my father, yes, yes. It was the very same thing I - I went - one year - I was
 in the fire service, and I went to - Lord Edward Spencer Churchill's guest house, see one wing was - was put on - put aside, this was - was at Windsor, put aside for - people in the ARP - Civil Defence, Fire Service, Police, etcetera, and - the lady who 
was in charge, she used to say grace at every meals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What about politics, did your father take any interest in politics, was he interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, he wasn't interested in politics, I'll tell you why, because - he wasn't - he never - he w
as never naturalised you see. And not - not being able to read, you see, because if a person can read the news he can have a mind, and have a mind of his own. But as he - couldn't read, so it - it didn't interest him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 He didn't even discuss politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no, no, no, nothing - nothing at all like that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You don't know what his views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Was your mother interested at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no. No. She could read - Jewish books, but she couldn't read English books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would your father vote at an election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 He couldn't vote - if he wasn't naturalised he's not allowed to vote.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How did your parents spend their leisure time, when they weren't working, what would your father do with his spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 We
ll we'd play cards - that was the usual game, or draughts. He'd like a glass of beer. He wasn't drunkard but I mean he'd like his glass of beer. He used to have - friends, they used to go to a club, you know like a - a - people of every country, you see, 
he's - these - like - well call them refugees if you like, they come from a country and they all more or less mix together. You see, that is where he - he would go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 So they'd have the chance to speak their own language?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That's right, that's right
, sure. It's like if you see a person who's come from - somewhere near where you live, you soon make - make - make a fuss you understand, because you come from the same - place. See they - they say - they say they come from a - some sort of st - stole, yo
u see. If these people come from the same stotle they become - comrades. See the same thing in this country.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Was there anywhere women could go, were women allowed to go to these clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I don't - I don't know. That I wouldn't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did your mother ever go out by herself to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh we used to take her to the cinema. Or theatre. Variety.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You, her sons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, yes. Yes. Yes, very often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What time would your father get home in the eveing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Couldn't tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you think he'd spend many of his evenings at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, oh definitely. Oh yes, yes, sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would he go to pubs at all, your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well I told you, I said, he - he'd go for occasion - a drink - drinks you know. Many times h
e's asked - well a few times he's asked me to stay outside the pub while he goes and has a half a pint, but - he wasn't a drunkard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would your mother go into a pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Was this because she just didn't want to or would women not go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well, it wasn't - it wasn't - a right for women, because - for a woman to go into a pub or to smoke at them days - they were common. You understand? You see a woman smoking you'd say she's no good. Or to go and have a drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did your father take part in any sports at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, he used to play - cricket. He used to teach us how to box. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would that be through a sort of club of some sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no, out in the street more or less you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Was this quite popular in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh yes, quite, quite. It was so popular for that - I've see many times I've seen - the people - fighting in the street, take off their shirts, and knuckleduster fights. No boxing gloves, and fight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Was this not as a sport?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Just a fight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh yes, yes, yes, but they'd always take their shirt off, and - they would have a go. And there was no - intervals, you know. Carry on until they both had black eyes and that you know, they would stop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would that be illegal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well - it's unlegal - unlegal if you understand what I mean, no policeman there you know, they - they wouldn't fight if policemen were there you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Where would he play cricket?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Pardon? There was this green, this - 
where this church, you see, the church was here, there was a big green and there was railings around. Well the gates were open, you could always go through you see, have a game of cricket there. Away from the tombstones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 A sort of open green land?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did your father go to races at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Was he a betting man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
No. No, there was no - well - it wasn't as prominent as it - as it is today. Same as this foot - football was nothing - nothing like it is today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 There were football stadiums were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What was the nearest one people would go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 East Ham. East Ham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That was going round about 1910 or so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Mm. Yes. And then - then there - there's the Victoria Park. I mean - ther
e's many games played there. It's a very big open park for the public. Of course in the summer now they hold like concerts and all that you know. There's swings for the kiddies, there's - small type of zoo, there's a fishing - fishing - a boat lake there.
 They do fishing there. These small motor - boats. You know the \endash  the models.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were there any of those things there when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I don't think - not so much. Not so much. But - they've all - there was always like - playing cricket and foo
tball there. And of course - course it's all also used sometimes for the - the strikers, they hold meetings there. You know, when there's a strike on, sort of round about - East Way, where they hold the most - most crowds rally and speak you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Has that always been a place for holding strike meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh not so much, no, no, no, no, it's only - it's only recently. Yes. But it was always like there for sports. Yes. And of course there was a band used to play there as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That was there in the old days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 So people would often go there on a Sunday presumably?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh absolutely, any day, any day, but - of course - Saturday and Sunday - very often, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did your father and mother belong to any savings clubs or any sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
That I wouldn't know, but - I'll tell you a little story. Years ago - you see - at the time I'm speaking about - the enjoyment was having a piano. My mother saved up, paying off I don't know how much, but it couldn't have been a lot
, about seventy-five pound for - to buy a piano. The last five pounds she couldn't play - pay, because my father must have been - either sick - or he might have been waiting for some money to come from a job that he'd - that he did. She went to some - cou
sins - in the street, and she - she - was very well known, tried to borrow that five pound. She couldn't get it. 'Cos we were - only children at the time. They came}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1724601\charrsid209760 
 along, they took this piano sa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 y. After paying seventy pound - five pound to pay, they took the piano away. Of course she had to start again from scratch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 She didn't get any of her money back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Nothing. Nothing at all. There - there wasn't that law where - where they could - do it. See. And it happened with quite a lot of - thousands of 
people the same thing. And of course not knowing the law, they just couldn't do a thing about it. So she had to start again from scratch. And - get another piano. And of course that second one was paid off, 'cos we were getting older at the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 She must have been a very determined woman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, sure. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did they belong to any boot or sick clubs of any sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No. The only thing we did belong to was the HAS. The Health - the Health - the HAS - the Health - it was - it was like a
 kind of security, in case people went in hospitals, see, and the hospital, they paid all hospital - benefits, you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would that cover the whole family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes. Yes. Yes, more or less. Excuse me, I want to have a smoke.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would they have any sort of funeral insurances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Do you want to turn it off? Otherwise you get a blank don't you? Don't you get a blank? Father was - and we'd get the strap if we - yes, this - is true, it's right too, it is right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 There was a great difference between the generations wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh quite well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you feel particularly close to any one of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I don't think so, more or less the same, I suppose 
my younger brother I got on - best with. He was only about eighteen months younger than myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What about as a child, who did you play with when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well, all - all the boys in the street, the young boys in the street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would they be n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1724601\charrsid209760 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
ighbours children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Where would you play, in the street, anywhere else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 In the - in the - church grounds, or else in the street where I live.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you ever play in the garden or the yard behind your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, well - no, there was a garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you play in that garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no. Some - sometimes used to be - we used to box in there, in the garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You were keen on boxing as well were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh - it was all right. You have to learn to protect yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would children go into each other's homes to play often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, I used to go - about three - doors from where I lived there was a Salvation Army - and I was very friendly with the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1724601\charrsid209760 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760  L}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1724601\charrsid209760 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 eutenant}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1724601\charrsid209760 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 s son you see w
ho was in charge of the Salvation Army you see. And - I very often used to go into his - his house, and he used to come into my house. Even when I joined the Army, 1914/18 war - it was after some time, he came with a - I believe his father to my house, an
d
 - he - he was very disappointed that he - that I wasn't there. See I was in the army at the time. But of course he left a - mess - left a message you understand. And of course I mean - when I was - oh when I went on leave my parents told me all about it 
you know. Oh yes, and then the - I used to go round to my cousin, used to live up the street. You know, used to go into his house and he used to go into my house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you have many relations living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well - my mother - my mother, she had a 
- cousins living - living about - eight or nine houses away you see. And of course she - she used to go round to them and - her cousins used to come round to our place you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 If your mother was ill would the families help each other at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 O
h definitely, definitely, definitely. The one thing - one thing - I don't know why but in the - Jewish religion they always try to help each other. In ever sense, whatever it may be.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You mean if people were sort of hard up financial or they need people to help in the house or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh yes, definitely. But then - then there is - there is what they call the Jewish Board of Guardians. Anybody in - in need, can always go to the Jewish Board of Guardians and get help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Has that always existed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes. Yes, for a very long time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 If a Jewish man was out of work could he go to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh definitely, definitely, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Was he sure of getting help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh quite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How would they treat a person, what was their attitude, the Jewish Board of Guardi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1724601\charrsid209760 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 ns when you went to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well, I don't know, I haven't been there so I couldn't tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 But what do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well, they tried to - first of all they tried to make certain that - that - that a person - you see, 
they've got to have proof that a person needs this help. And if they're certain that they need this help they'll give them the help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you think they'd be used quite often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh I suppose so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 So if a person newly arrived in this country, could he go to them for help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1724601\charrsid209760 Well - in the ordin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
ary way, if a person comes to a strange country - the best thing that I myself would suggest, is they go to the - Embassy, whichever country they belong to. And they can give 'em the information - where to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you think they would have done that in the early years of the century?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
That I don't know. You see, very often - I've had letters, because - being Secretary - I've had letters - from various Embassies, and I've given them information that has come in very handy to them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 They then pass it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
That's right, that's right, yes, yes. Mm. Many times - I've been - you know, thanked for it, you know what I mean, letter of thanks and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Was there a branch of the Jewish Board of Guardians in this area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Yes. It used to be in - what they call Petticoat Lane, the top of Petticoat Lane is - is - well it's Middlesex Street towards Bishopsgate. Well they moved after the - after this last war. Now they're at - somewhere in the
 West End. I don't know exactly where but if anybody looks in the telephone book they can always find it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were you free to play with any children you pleased or were you discouraged from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no, we could play with anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
There were so - so few coloured people that if you saw - if you see a coloured person, you'd say to yourself, well he's going to bring me luck. That was the saying. There - there - I would say there was about one - one - in about - ten
 thousand. Understand? One black person in about ten thousand of the ordinary population.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 And he'd be working on a ship or something would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well, perhaps - no, perhaps passing through the street you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 It was probably a very mixed community round here though was it, the question of language?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh yes. Yes, yes. Well - I - I think I - I don't know if I told - ever told - I don't know if I ever told you that - about the time - when I - first joined the Fire Service, Cable Street, tha
t is - towards the docks - there was something else - something else I wanted to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You said something about Cable Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, yes. Yes, there was a fire alarm, 'cos these fire alarms now are done away with, but being a Jewish quarter, t
hey had - on the notice - you see for - the English person, person who could read - break the glass, pull the bell and wait 'til the fire comes. 'Til the engine comes. But the Jewish words were - brak the glaz, see, that's break the glass, see this clip, 
t
hat's pull the - the nob and vat viz the machine cund, and wait till the engine comes. A pal of - pal of mine who was in the fire service, he was wearing full uniform, metal - steel helmet, gas mask on - on his back, and he had his photo, somebody took hi
s
 photo - with - with that fire alarm in them words. So that must be a real souvenir today, because today the fire alarm's are done away with. Now even when I first joined the Fire Service, we used to go out for - instructions. They used to open the fire a
l
arm, and - that fire alarm had like similar to a telephone, you know, when you put down the telephone you got a thing that presses you see, well you had to put your - hand on there, you see and speak - you see, but if you pressed it, it meant pulling down
 
the bells in the - in the station, see a red eye would come out and the bells would come down and out would come the firemen you see on their engines. Well that's one thing you - had - mustn't do. You see, we'll say you're calling from - from fire alarm n
u
mber so and so - you're giving the test, is test all right mate? Say, yes, and - you'd - put the - like receiver back, you close the box, you go to the next fire alarm, then you keep on the same - saying the same thing. Well then they brought out another 
t
ype of fire alarm, it was so complicated - that they would only allow the officers - station officers, sub-officers and company officers to test the fire alarms. And they also used to have a blackboard and they gave - a diagram, showing exactly what to do
.
 Now it was so complicated that if you did anything wrong - that - the same thing would happen, they'd bring out the engines you see. And 'course - they asked for volunteers like the men to - test fire alarms and nobody would do it. So I says to one offic
e
r one day I says, do you mind if I go out with you, because I was on watchman duty. He said, certainly. He went out and he showed me - they showed you theory and practise. Practise, you can learn the second, theory is complicated. He showed me the first o
n
e, he says, you - can you understand it? I says, yes. I went to the second one, the third one, I says - when I went back to the station I says to the boys, it's a bit of cake. And 'course after that they all went out, you see. And they enjoyed going out b
ecause it was a break from - you know, from - from the indoor routine. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you say you later on did join a youth organisation of some sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, I joined the - Polytechnic. In Hackney.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh I - when I - that was when I came out of the fire - out of the Fire Service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That was later on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What about when you were a boy, did you belong to any youth clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, no. No, no. You see, the trouble was I was - as I told you before? The mas
ters - didn't inform us - in fact - we had to go ourselves to try to find a job. Actually I wanted to go into an office. Because - without boasting I was top boy in the class. But - I was very interested in - office work because I was very good at figures
.
 I was at - I was good at writing and essays and all that, and the trouble was - I mean, I know myself, being a Jew - that English firms wouldn't take me on. My first job, I tried to get a job at Kierley and Tongs, they were very - very big provision merc
hants, and - no job. Then I went to two or three other places, no job. The finish, after walking - walking my legs off, I found a job in a grocery shop. Starting wage half a crown a week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 There really was prejudice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Definitely. Definitely, of co
urse it was. It's the very same thing as today. Without influence, you understand, you can't get no big jobs. It was the very same thing in the Fire Service. They used to pay - paste - put up notices on on the - on the notice boards. Firemen, who've been 
i
n the Fire Service - three years, two years, become experienced firemen. When it come to jobs unless you had degrees you had no chance at all. There was one fellow there, he was a sub-officer. A sub-officer is a leader of men. He goes out to fires, he - h
e
 tells 'em what to do and he does the job right. In fact we were complimented by some of the brass hats, because they thought at the time that - we were rookies, we didn't know what it was all about, but we learnt the same as anybody else. Now this fellow
,
 he went up in front of a - examination board, they found out he had flat feet, because he had flat feet he wasn't a - he wasn't any good. The ordinary firemen, when they first joined, they took - people from the Navy, because they understand - they knew 
a
ll about knots, and they understood discipline. Now a fireman could be in the Fire Service before the war, the London Fire Brigade, fifteen or twenty years, and he'd be - he could never - go up the ladder. You understand? But when the war broke out, all t
h
ese firemen, they all become station officers, because they only become station officers up 'til the time - the war existed. After the war they had to go back to their ordinary rank. By that time - by that time they're already men of retirement age, so of
 
course more or less they retired. That's the trouble. Without influence, you haven't got influence, I mean to say, a rich man's son can be put into a good job, straight away. A poor man, he's got to start from the bottom and he - he's got no chance at all
. Oh definitely, sure, yes, yes. Yes, sure. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What did you do during your free time while you were still a schoolboy, did you have any hobbies you were interested in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you keep any pets?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you collect anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Not a collector of anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you do gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh I used to help a bro- my brother. I won't say I was a gardener but I used to help him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 He was interested in gardening was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh he was - yes
, very interested. He made a lovely garden. In fact, even - even there was a tree in the other yard - the - the yard, you see, a low - a low low brick wall you understand. People who had it before, they - they had a - sacks beca}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12256682\charrsid209760 use - they used to - have sack }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
of old clothing you know they used to sell, and that yard was very nearly filled up with all these sacks, it was a big yard, and - there was a tree growing there right at the back, and - I helped him one night, we dig that tree up and planted it in our 
garden. And - it turned out into a lovely tree afterwards you know what I mean, of course nobody - nobody - ever - spoke about the tree being over there, in fact they didn't - worry them at all you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 It's amazing that it ever rooted though really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes, yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you do any sort of sports, did you play any sports at all when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well, I used to play football, football in school, or cricket in school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 But not on the weekends you didn't play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Once - once I went fishing - this was here when I went away to a place called Fleet in Hampshire, and there was a couple of boys there, only - they would have been only small at the time, fishing. And one boy fell in - fell in - fell i
n the river but they got him out you know. Tat was funny.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you have a bicycle when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh yes, yes, yes. We both had bicycles. And I remember we were both wearing new - new suits, my brother and myself, and it didn't - raining - 
first he fell down then I fell down, in the mud, yes, we had to brush ourselves and - you know, make sure that when we got indoors you know they were - but nobody noticed it you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you go for on a bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I used to go to - well when - 
when I got a bit older I used to go to - there was a place, a - a regular - place where we used to go, it was called Riddledown. Riddlesdown. It's - Elephant and Castle - Elephant and Castle way - over - past the Oval, on the way going to Brighton but not
 so far. But that was a very nice - ride. Yes, many times I used to go there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 The roads must have been very free?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, of course they were, oh definitely, definitely. Oh it was a pleasure to - you know, at that time to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were there a lot of bicycles about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh yes, yes. Bicycles and tandems. The tandem bikes. In fact my elder brother - he used to run a tan - tandem club. Yes, this one who used to do the gardening. And - he used to - he used to make - he made - and even then - then o
nce in a while by evening - like we - you have a - a jolly - a jolly at night. He bought a barrel of beer and yet he - he never drank a drop himself, because he was temperance. Yes. He used to bring - he - in a gla - like glass blower. Many things he used
 to bring home, you know, very - these very long thing, you know glass. Well is there anything else to - speak about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you ever go to any concerts or theatres or music halls when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well I think I told you I did used to go to musi
c halls. There used to be the London - the London in Shoreditch. The Olympia, also in Shoreditch. The Cambridge Theatre in - Commercial Street. There was the Wonderland, in the Whitechapel Road. That was also - a boxing - for boxing, all kinds of sport - 
a few booths outside with - snake charmers and things like that. And there was one fellow in particular, a very good boxer, his name was Hack - Hackensmitt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would he have boxing displays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no. Oh yes, yes - wrestling. Werestling. Wrestling. Oh
 yes, yes. Oh that was a well known place. And the Whitechapel Road of a Saturday, they used to have coconut shies there. And the - jockey scales. In fact - the Mile End Waste was - was a sight - a sight worthwhile seeing. And stalls of every description 
there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 When did that stop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Say after the first world war. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 It changed character completely?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes. Yes, completely. Then the - then the Wonderland in the Commercial Road - that - that would - that was also changed after the first wor
ld war and come - and become a cinema, it was called the Reveille, and next the - next to that used to be - the old - it used to be a station called St Mary's station.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you go to the cinema at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes. Yes, yes. Quite a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would there be quite a lot of cinemas at the same time as music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 There were hun - there were hundreds, hundreds of cinemas. All over the place. In the Whitechapel Road there must have be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 n about - ten or twelve cinemas, say from the Whitechapel Road - 
up to - what they call Burdett Road. There was also a cinema in Aldgate itself, from - from the Leman Street, up to Mansell Street. There was a cinema there. And there was quite a lot of provision shops and - tobacconist shops and all that. Tea shops.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I suppose this was the great age of the cinema wasn't it when it first started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, yes, sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did they used to be crowded?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 How much would it cost to go in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 About nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
pence. About nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 pence. Nine old pennies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Could people afford that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well, they managed, they managed all right, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Did you get any pocket money, were you given any regular pocket money by your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 I suppose we must have got but I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you know what you'd spend it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well - when I first started - when I first started on my job I had sixpence. And I couldn't spend it. That's a fact. I mean today you spend a pound like nothing, you can't even see it. But I used to have sixpence pocket mon
ey and I couldn't spend it. I remember I bought my first week's - the first work - week I worked there - I know my pocket money was sixpence so I gave my mother two shillings, I had half a crown you see. I bought a tray, that would - that - if you bought 
it today, a tea tray, metal tea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
tray - you'd have to pay at least fifteen shillings. Bought at - in what they call an oil shop. I paid - I paid sixpence for that tray. We had that tray for years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You said your relations would come and help your mother if ever she needed any help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would your parents bring friends to the house, would they enter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760 t}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 ain friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, definitely. Sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 They would invite them into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, yes, quite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 And would they go and visit other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, oh yes, certainly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would they be offered anything to eat or drink when they came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh definitely, definitely, the first thing's a cup of tea. Without a cup of tea you're not friends. And it's - it's an -
 it's an insult if you do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
't have a cup of tea, whether they make it strong or whether they make it weak. I remember going to a pal of mine in - in - Dorking, he was a expert - billiard player so he had a job - he had a billiard hall if you understand, he 
was in charge, and - I went there with - my wife - took her there for the first time, and they make - they made us both - two cups of tea, it was - it was worse than beer. It was black, it was strong, well - we couldn't drink it. But you - one thing you m
ust never refuse is - is the very same thing, if anybody gives you a present, how small a present is or how big, you must always accept it. Because otherwise there's bad feeling. Yes. Even if you got half a dozen of one thing you must always accept.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 So even in the early days you remember people were offered tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh definitely, definitely. Yes, yes. That's the first things, a cup of tea you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would they be your mother's friends who'd come into the house or your father's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well - more
 - I'd say more my mother's friends. Because my father must have had some brothers but - we never ever saw them. Whether they were still back in their - the - their - his country, I mean I don't know, but - I couldn't ask no questions like - like that you
 know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would people call in casually in those days without an invitation or did they have to wait to be invited?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh no, no, they'd come casually. Yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What about neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, we were - we were very respected yo
u see, especially pcos my father - he - I - I don't think there was a single neighbour who didn't know - know him in the house, you can understand, you see, 'cos - he used to collect the rents, he used to do any jobs that wanted doing, and - he was well l
i
ked. In fact - one day - this was after the first - after the first world war, big furniture was in fashion. After the war there's always plenty of money, you see. And my father, he wished to buy a sideboard. Now - I at the time was - going to - various s
a
le rooms and I says to him, well, if you wait until there's a sale advertised because I used to buy a paper called the Daily Telegraph, I says, there's always sales advertised, I says, when there's some sideboards advertised you'll come with me. Well - I 
p
icked up a paper one day and there was some sideboards there you see besides other furniture, and - we - went to Fulham Road. And - I got in the auction room, I - that was the first time I've ever been in this auction room, and we had to wait a certain ti
m
e until this sideboard came up, you see, like for auction. Now the auctioneer, he gave a speech about this sideboard, he says it's come out of a noble man's house, he says, it's in a very fine condition, and expects to start the bid off at three figures. 
W
ell three figures is the hundred pound. Well nobody in the saleroom would - they were all silent. And me - being forward, I offered him ten pound, he very nearly fell through his rostrum. So he says, very well, it's a bid. Well - then people start bidding
,
 ten pound, eleven pound, twelve pound, thirteen - fourteen pound, you know went like that. I go up to sixteen pound, you see. Now nobody else bid, all of a sudden like somebody else screams out, seventeen pound. I turned round, it was my father. So the a
u
ctioneer says, any more of you sir? I said, no, me old man's bidding against me. So he knocked it down for seventeen pound, 'cos he had the honour of buying it, you see, I'd done all the spade work and he followed up. Well - he bought his sideboard, and d
o
 you know, when ever a person get - gets a new toy they always like to show it to people. So of course he called the neighbours in to see it, it was such a wonderful art - article. And - somebody offered him twenty pound and somebody offered him fifty pou
n
d and somebody offered him sixty pound, and we had an uncle - he was a - in the - plywood - plywood importer, he had a place in Kinsell Road like a - a - you know, where he used to keep all his timber. He see this sideboard, he says, that sideboard, he sa
y
s, looked after will last another two or three hundred years. Well at the finish, he sold it for eighty-five pound. Well my father seeing that there's money in furniture, he started going with me to sales. He borrowed some money from a sister of mine, and
 
he started and - he done quite well for himself. But - what I - I'm trying to say is that - 'course he told the neighbours and other neighbours told oth - other people, you know what I mean, they all come - they all wanted to see this wonderful article. T
hat's what I'm trying to say is they -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 It was a piece of furniture?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 That's right, that's right. And also that - he knew all the neighbours and all the neighbours knew him you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 People often say that in those days they made their own amusements.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, definitely. Definitely. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What would people do with their time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Well, I - I think I explained before - playing the piano - having evening in, boys and girls - somebody bringing a bottle of wine and somebody
 else bringing a bottle of whisky, you see, and - there was even a gramophone, you know, the old fashioned gramophone - the one you see like - like a - His Master's Voice, the one with a long horn, you turned the handle, know what I mean, because there wa
s no electricity in them days, you had to t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760 urn the handle round - and - he}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
r - play records and sing and - then somebody would give a turn, my wife used to do the - Apache, because she - she was - a very jolly girl in them days you know. In fact through - th
at is how we got to know each other you see. And - there would be singing, my sister would - play the piano. In fact she used to play the piano in the picture places as well you know. Yes, yes, she played quite well. Otherwise we - of a Sunday we'd play a
 - we'd play cards. You know, bro - all the - brothers and sisters would come together, even we - when we were married we - we used to come home every Sunday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You'd all go back to your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 You still regarded that as your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, quite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Many people divide society into different social classes or groups, before 1918 would you say that some belonged to one class or one group, would you look at it like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Beg - regarding what, regarding -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Do you think people }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760 were in different social classe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 s?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, yes, 'course there was, you mean - you mean like - like - middle class. First class. Yes, definitely. Definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What classes do you think there were then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 There was the middle class - high class. And the - and the poorer classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What group would you have put yourself in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 In the poorer class. Oh definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What sort of people would you say belonged to the same group as you? In this area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well most working people. All working people. To be middle class you were - you were on the - on the higher scale.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Who would be in the middle class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760 ty}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
pe of - we won't - I won't say electronic because there was no such thing as electronic but - the more brainy people - earning the bigger wage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Would you say it was easy to move from the poorer class into the middle class at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 What was the only way you could do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 The supposition, the person - the per
son that become a - a - he joined the Masonic Lodge, see, he - he would be second class. See? Once they join - once they joined the Masonic Lodge, they're on the way - on the way up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were there branches of the Masons round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Oh yes, oh yes, 
yes, yes, my brother-in-law was a Mason. He started off - he was a - manager in the tailoring trade. Once he joined the Masons he become a - an accountant. You see, things change. From that - when the war broke out he was - he was working with the Board o
f
 Trade, see, influence, with the Board of Trade, and he had - in case of any trouble he had two - Sidey - two CID - plainclothes men he could call on any time. He could go to a place like - I'm speaking about a big place - say a place like - Tesco's if yo
u like, he could go into the - holy of holy office, where they've got a terrific safe, he could ask to see their books. In case of any black}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14440260\charrsid209760  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 market you understand. See, and there was plenty of - all that about, he could go to a place like Jeremiah Rotherham
s, in Shoreditch, to any place, any of these very big places. And - ask to see their books. And of course straight away it's bribery. You understand what I mean? They either - going to take it or they're not going to take it. Well I won't tell you any mor
e about that because I'd tell you a story. That's what I call middle class. You see, and then - and then they can take these - big houses. 'Cos them days they were six hundred pound, today they're about - umpteen thousand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were you ever brought up to t
reat people of one sort differently from another, did you ever have to bow or show respect to anyone or touch your cap, was that ever expected of you when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Well, not as a boy but when I first joined the army - there used - the saluting business, and yet the Americans don't do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 They're more democratic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Yes, yes, sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Was there anyone you ever called sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Schoolmaster, yes. Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Anyone else, any friends of the family or anyone you came across?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 No, I don't think so. Unless - unless it was - applying for a job, or it might have been at a Labour Exchange.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10036353 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 Were your parents ever referred to as sir or madam or shown respect by people raising their cap to them, was it done much in those days?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8133147 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4859080\charrsid209760 
Oh - oh in the street say ourselves, yes, yes, there was quite a lot of raising your hat. Yes. So when you meet somebody say, you know what I mean, good afternoon or good day, yes, there was quite a lot.
